  "analysis": "We inspected the COBOL source and data files. The COBOL program reads a single input record from src/INPUT.DAT containing buyer ID (4 chars), seller ID (4 chars), book ID (4 chars), and amount (digits). It validates buyer and seller exist in ACCOUNTS.DAT, that the book exists in BOOKS.DAT, and that the book owner equals the seller. If validation passes, it subtracts amount from the buyer's ACCOUNT-BALANCE, adds to seller's, updates the BOOK-OWNER to the buyer, and appends a new record to TRANSACTIONS.DAT. Records are fixed-width with no newlines: ACCOUNTS 34 bytes per record (4+20+10), BOOKS 28 bytes (4+20+4), TRANSACTIONS 22 bytes (4+10+4+4). We compiled and ran the COBOL program; with the given INPUT.DAT (U001U002B007200) the book B007 does not exist, so the program failed validation and did not modify data. We backed up initial data and captured the COBOL output snapshot in data.cobol.out. We now need to implement program.py to replicate the logic and produce identical file outputs. Because the COBOL run resulted in no changes, our Python run from the same initial state should also result in no changes and match the COBOL outputs. We'll implement precise fixed-width parsing and writing, with zero-padded numeric fields, and execute the Python script, then compare outputs.",
  "plan": "1) Create /app/program.py implementing the same logic: fixed-width parsing of ACCOUNTS.DAT, BOOKS.DAT, TRANSACTIONS.DAT; parse INPUT.DAT fields; perform validation per COBOL; update files only if validation passes; append transaction record on success; print the same messages for empty input or validation/success.
2) Make the script executable.
3) Ensure /app/data is restored to the initial snapshot (already done), then run the Python script from /app.
4) Copy resulting data files to data.python.out.
5) Compare data.python.out files with data.cobol.out to confirm identical content.
